{/* 模块名称 */"module_name": "Expression Matrix Preprocessing",/* 分析目标描述 */"goal": "Preprocess the metabolomics expression matrix (2059 metabolites \u00d718 samples) for downstream statistical analysis, including missing value imputation, normalization, log transformation, and median scaling. The data originates from a murine CDI model with three experimental groups: high-iron diet before infection (FE, n=6), Clostridium difficile infection alone (CD, n=6), and healthy standard control (NC, n=6).",/* 所需输入文件路径列表 */"input_files": ["G:/OmicsWorks/test/metabolism/expression.csv","G:/OmicsWorks/test/metabolism/sampleinfo.csv"],/* 预期输出文件路径列表 */"output_files": ["G:/OmicsWorks/test/metabolism/tmp/expression_preprocessed.csv"],"execution_steps": [{"action": "Load expression matrix. Read CSV with first column (unnamed) as row names (metabolite IDs). The matrix has2059 rows \u00d718 columns (Fc16YH_CD1-6, Fc16YH_FE1-6, Fc16YH_NC1-6). Validate sample names against sampleinfo.csv. QC samples (Fc16YH_QC01-03) exist in sampleinfo.csv but are absent from the expression matrix \u2014 they are ignored.","goal": "Load raw data into R data.frame/matrix with proper row names (molecule IDs) and column names (sample IDs).","rscript_path": null},{"action": "Missing value imputation per row. For each metabolite row, compute the minimum positive value. If any NA/NaN values exist in that row, replace them with half of that minimum positive value. Note: Initial data inspection confirms0 NAs and0 zeros \u2014 this step is a no-op but is retained for pipeline robustness.","goal": "Eliminate missing values to ensure downstream operations (log transform, normalization) run without errors.","rscript_path": null},{"action": "Column sum normalization (relative abundance). For each sample column, sum all metabolite values. Divide each value by its column sum so each sample's intensities sum to1. This corrects for global differences in total metabolite abundance between samples (e.g., due to concentration variations or injection volume differences).","goal": "Normalize to relative expression scale, removing systematic variation in total metabolite load across samples.","rscript_path": null},{"action": "Log2 transformation. Check if any value exceeds100 in the normalized data. Raw data max =283.38 (>100) indicating non-log scale, so apply log2(x) transformation. If any values become exactly0, add a small positive constant (half of the global minimum positive value) before log transform to avoid -Inf.","goal": "Transform data to log2 scale to stabilize variance, reduce skewness, and make fold-changes symmetric.","rscript_path": null},{"action": "Median scaling per molecule (row). For each metabolite, compute the median value across all18 samples. Subtract this median from each value in the row (centering). Optionally divide by median absolute deviation (MAD) for unit scaling. This centers each metabolite's expression at zero, making up/down regulation patterns comparable across metabolites of vastly different abundances.","goal": "Median-center each metabolite so positive values = above-median expression, negative = below-median expression, enabling cross-metabolite comparisons.","rscript_path": null},{"action": "Validation and export. Check final matrix dimensions (2059 \u00d718), verify no NaN/Inf values introduced, confirm row names (metabolites) and column names (samples) are preserved. Write the preprocessed matrix as CSV with molecule IDs as the first column.","goal": "Ensure data integrity and save the clean, preprocessed matrix for downstream differential analysis and visualization.","rscript_path": null}],"notes": "This is a metabolomics dataset (2059 annotated metabolites) from a murine CDI study. No user-specified preprocessing exceptions were found in the research topic. The standard pipeline applies: (1) missing value imputation \u2014 safe step (0 NAs detected), (2) column sum normalization to relative abundance, (3) log2 transformation (required because max =283.38 >100, indicating original non-log scale; only2 out of2059 metabolites exceed100), (4) median scaling per row. QC sample columns (Fc16YH_QC01-03) exist in sampleinfo.csv but not in the expression matrix, so they require no handling. The molecule annotation file (metabolites.csv,2172 entries with KEGG IDs, HMDB IDs, chemical classes) can be linked to the preprocessed matrix for downstream pathway enrichment and metabolite classification.",/* 阶段性总结文本 */"conclusion": "","comparisons": null}